The description mentions that node1 and node2 form a cycle (which they do), but that's a red herring - the actual bug is the null pointer dereference on node3.

ROOT CAUSE: program.cpp:19 - The code attempts to dereference `node3->next`, which is nullptr (initialized by the constructor and never assigned). When the program tries to copy-construct a Node object `n` from `*node3->next`, it attempts to read memory at address 0x0 (null pointer), causing a segmentation fault. The underlying defect is that the code unconditionally dereferences a pointer that may be null without checking its validity first.

LOCAL FIX: Before dereferencing `node3->next`, check if it's not null. Replace line 19:
```cpp
