Node n = *node3->next;
```

GLOBAL FIX: Use smart pointers (std::shared_ptr or std::unique_ptr) and optional types to make null pointer handling explicit and safer. Replace raw pointers with `std::shared_ptr<Node>` and use a method that returns `std::optional<Node>` or `std::shared_ptr<Node>` to make null cases explicit. Better yet, redesign the linked list API to use iterator patterns or range-checked accessors that throw exceptions or return optional values instead of allowing direct pointer dereferencing. This ensures that null pointer accesses are either impossible (by construction) or explicitly handled at the type level:
```cpp
#include <memory>
#include <optional>

class Node {
public:
    int data;
    std::shared_ptr<Node> next;

    Node(int value) : data(value), next(nullptr) {}

    std::optional<Node> safeDerefNext() const {
        if (next) return *next;
        return std::nullopt;
    }
};
```
